Security Operations Fundamentals > [T1]: Security Operation Centers (SOC) - Overview

What is a Security Operation Center (SOC)?

The security operations center is the centralized unit within the organization where most of the defense operations and practices are performed." The SOC is not only the physical facility but includes the technology, processes, and people (Team).  

According to TechTarget:

"A security operations center (SOC) is a command center facility for a team of information technology (IT) professionals with expertise in information security (infosec) who monitors, analyzes, and protects an organization from cyber-attacks."

The following picture illustrates a Security Operation Center facility:
 

Figure - zoom in

Three essential elements and cornerstones make up a successful and effective security operation center. SOC and information security, in general, are not only about technology and deploying technical security measures and controls. The core elements of a SOC are the following:

  1. People: refers to the team and human resources that operate and manage the Security Operation Center. Hiring the right people is very important to running an efficient SOC. We will discuss this point later in depth. 

  2. Technology: refers to the technical stack of tools the SOC team uses to perform security operations. For example, which firewall -type and vendor- should be used and with which capabilities?

  3. Process: refers to the "How" aspect, which means how SOC analysts will use technology to achieve SOC goals and objectives. For example, what steps to take in case of intrusion, in which order, and by which job role?


These three pillars are called "The people, process, technology (PPT) framework." Bruce Schneier, a well-known security expert and cryptographer, introduced this model. Since then, many others have leveraged this framework in various security areas. Realizing the potential of combining the three elements, many organizations worldwide started using the PPT framework.
 

Figure 2 - zoom in


Security Operation Centers (SOC) have many core functions and services. Some of them are the following:

  • Alert Management: receiving alerts from different devices and investigating them.
  • Incident Response: preparing and responding to cyber-attacks.
  • Log Management: ensuring that essential logs required to perform security operations are collected and parsed. Parsing is the process of splitting unstructured log data into attributes and allowing them to be processed by different security solutions. 
  • Compliance Management: ensuring the organization complies with industry standards. For example, organizations in the healthcare industry have to comply with the HIPAA standard.
  • Malware Analysis: analyzing malicious files discovered on compromised systems to understand how the malware works, what it does, and who possibly developed it.
  • Threat Hunting: hunting for attackers flying under the radar. Some attackers can sneak in unnoticed despite the SOC's maturity and capabilities. Detecting them requires manual hunting to search places where the existing detection is blind.
  • Digital Forensics: analyzing compromised systems (e.g., operating system logs, applications logs, etc.) and figuring out the attacker's performed actions.


All these core functions work together to achieve a bigger goal - to improve the organization's cyber defense capability. That is not a comprehensive list and may differ from one organization to another depending on many factors (i.e., size, maturity, budget, etc.).

The following lessons will discuss SOC's core components, people, processes, and technology and how they work together to achieve SOC's mission.
